But when 1 had seriously considered the matter, the aeid spirit ol nitre seemed to be too ponderous and fixed to circulate as a whole through the very thin air. Besides, the nitro-aerini salt, whatever it may be, . becomes food for lires, and also passes into the blood of animals by means of respiration, as will be shown below. But the acid spirit ol nitre, being humid and extremely corrosive, is fitted rather lor extinguishing flame and the life of animals, than for sustaining them.

But although the spirit of nitre does not proceed altogether from the air, still we must believe that some part ol it originates from the air. For, since some part of the nitre is derived from the air, as has been shown above, while the fixed salt, ol which nitre in part consists, proceeds from the earth, the remainder of the nitre, that is to say, its aeid and fiery spirit, must be derived, in part at least, from the air. But in order that the aerial part of the spirit of nitre may be better understood, we must brieliy premise the following.
